entries

public static <K,V> Set<Map.Entry<K,V>> entries(Map<K,V> m)
Returns a Set view of the entries contained in this map.

This method should always be preferred instead of iterating a maps keys and invoking get() on each iteration. The following code should never be used: 

 
 Map map = [...]
 for (final String key : map.keySet()) {
     String value = map.get(key);
     // do something with key/value
 }
Instead, write: 
 
 Map map = [...]
 for (final Entry e : entries(map)) {
     // do something with e.getKey/e.getValue
 }

Parameters:
m - Map; may be null
Returns:
Set of map entries

index

public static <T> T[] index(Class<T> cls,
                            Map<Integer,T> map)
Returns an array-based variant of the provided indexed map. This method should not be used if any of the keys used are greater than the size of the map. This is very useful if you have a map where each value is given an index starting from zero. This is a very common pattern in the BEL framework.

Here is an example where the use of this method would be beneficial. Given some list of 100,000 elements, an index is assigned to each element of the list: 

 
 Map map = sizedHashMap(list.size());
 for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {
     map.put(i, list.get(i));
 }
A typical use of map follows: 
 
 for (int i = 0; i < map.size(); i++) {
     MyObject m = map.get(i);
     // use "m"
 }
The problem with such code is the costly invocation to Map.get(Object) on every iteration. This becomes very expensive with very large collections.

Different ways of accessing the data becomes necessary (for example, using a list structure and calling List.get(int), see guidelines below). Taking this a step further, we can very easily rewrite this map as an array and get considerable speed improvements. 

 
 
 MyObject[] indexed = index(map);
 for (int i = 0; i < indexed.length; i++) {
     MyObject m = indexed[i];
     // use "m"
 }
Whatever costs you pay up front for indexing the map quickly vanish on each iteration of the loop.

Guidelines

Considering the following as a good baseline when it comes to using large numbers of objects.
  1. Map.get(Object) can be fast when using optimized maps and hash functions though will usually perform worse than lists.
  2. List.get(int) almost always beats Map.get(Object) in performance.
  3. Index access into an array always beats accessing either a list or map.

Parameters:
map - The map to index. The keys used by the map should never be greater than the size of the map. Under ideal conditions, each value 0 <= x < = map.size() should have a key assigned. Otherwise, the resulting array will waste memory (i.e., it will be a spare array).
Returns:
T[]

Returns a hash map of type K, V optimized to the specified capacity and load factor.

Use optimized hash maps when the capacity of a hash map is known to be greater than sixteen (the default initial capacity) and a load factor is desired to control resizing behavior. The hash map implementation will automatically adjust the size to the next nearest power of two.

Parameters:
